observations.recommendation:
We recommended the following to the Local Chief Executive:
Reconstitute the Inventory Committee, but ensure that no member is at retirable age during the conduct of the one-time cleansing;
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain Property 	Ledger Cards and to derecognize properties that do not qualify the 	capitalization threshold of PPE;
Instruct the management to claim the copy of the Deed of Donation 	from  the PCSO, as it has been confirmed that the document is now available, and to prepare an authorization if the claimant is acting on behalf of the mayor;
Instruct the GSO to maintain Property Cards for PPEs; and
As regards to the Road Networks, require the Accountant and GSO 	to establish proper records for the Road Networks, and for the Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical count of the road assets.

We recommended that Local Chief Executive:
Revisit current staffing situation at the Municipal Accounting’s Office to verify issue on manpower shortage. If this is the case, consider recruitment of staff or provide augmentation of personnel to help in the accounting office, as necessary;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant for the immediate submission of Statement of Comparison of Budget and Actual Amounts and  its reconciliation, and the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended to the management to:
Instruct the HRMO to directly inform the personnel responsible in the preparation of the payroll any updates on employee promotions and retirements, and to coordinate with the accounting any changes in payroll withholdings that require adjustments;
Direct the Municipal HRMO and Municipal Accountant to make a formal representation to the GSIS Office for the reconciliation of their respective records, in case unreconciled balance still persist after compliance on the immediately preceding recommendation.

We recommended that management:
Secure Approved Travel Order and Itinerary of Travel before granting of Cash Advance to Officers and Employees;
Provide manpower temporarily to assist the Special Disbursing Officer (SDO) in the liquidation of the advances;
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to stop the granting of additional cash advance unless the previous cash advance given is first settled or proper accounting thereof is made; and
Demand immediate settlement of cash advances and/or cause the withholding of the amount due from the concerned officials and employees to compel them to settle their accounts. Management may resort to legal action if no settlement is made after sending three (3) demand letters.

Enjoin the General Services Officer to maintain Property Cards and conduct physical inventory of all municipal properties and to prepare and submit the Report on the Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment;
Enjoin the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards;
Provide the GSO Designate with an office and enough manpower to support his function and to lighten his load in the Treasury Office;
Transfer the accounts booked under the Trust Fund to the General Fund and recognize the depreciation in the General Fund books;
Direct the GSO to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer to prepare the road map of the municipality to facilitate the preparation of a proper inventory and reporting of the municipality’s road network system; and
Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the MNAO to secure the Acknowledgement Receipt of In-Kind Donations and submit to management for its inclusion in the related quarterly report;
Direct the MNAO to stockpile the donated goods according to the standard tier-high and transfer the goods in a better-secured location.

We recommended that management:
Require the MAO, MNAO and the LDRRMO to submit to the GSO and the Municipal Accountant the Acknowledgement Receipts of the donations they have received and the list of beneficiaries with whom the donations were distributed, copy furnished the Office of the Auditor;
Streamline and document its donation policy and process thru the issuance of an Executive Order or a Memorandum, which among others, would contain the employees authorized to receive donations and their reportorial responsibilities.

We recommended that management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to draw an adjusting entry to recognize previously recorded expenses amounting to P840,221 as inventories;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to maintain and update the stock cards for each inventory item;
Direct the GSO, RHU and Municipal Accountant to conduct physical inventory-taking on items under the custody of the RHU;
Instruct the GSO and the RHU to submit a distribution list on the items cited if such inventories were already dispensed;
Remind the RHU to submit a distribution list covering items received from prior requisition, as supporting document for prospective/intended requisitions addressed to the GSO.

We recommended that management:
Direct the MHO and the MENRO to coordinate with the DOH on the best course of action for the transport and disposal of COVID-19 wastes;
Instruct the MENRO to integrate COVID-19 Waste Management Plan in the LGU’s Solid Waste Management Plan;
Advice the Local Development Council to review the programs under the Annual Investment Plan for the possible inclusion of program related to COVID-19 Waste Management.

We recommended that management:
Require the HRMO to review the personnel schedule and job functions of the GSO and the Accounting Office, and provide for staff augmentation, if necessary;
Create an inventory committee composed of an adequate number of members with members from the Accounting Unit and Treasury Unit (in the absence of a separate Supply Unit) and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:
Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;
Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE under their accountability, if any;
Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/ personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries

We recommended that management:
Require the contractor of projects with budgetary provision for public notification, to immediately install the required billboards at the project sites and/or accomplish completely the required information within fifteen (15) days from receipt hereof, otherwise the budgetary provision of the notification shall be disallowed in audit;
Instruct the municipal engineer to closely monitor compliance by the contractors on the requirements set forth under COA Circular 2013-004, for future projects that will be undertaken.

We recommended that management:
Require the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Budget Officer and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records on the unexpended LDRRMF, presented by year;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to timely transfer the unexpended LDRRMF to the special trust fund;
Enjoin the Municipal Budget Officer to exercise prudence in obligating expenses from prior year’s unexpended LDRRMF which partakes as a trust fund.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to coordinate with the ETHRACS service-provider for a systems upgrade with the two-fold goal to hasten data processing and provide additional program functions; otherwise, consider sourcing another service provider to deliver the needed service;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit to the Municipal Accountant the List of Basic RPT Delinquencies since C.Y. 2002, as reference of the accountant’s adjustment in the RPT and SET receivables.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer, the SIWASS Manager and the Collecting Officers to impose the interest for late payments of water bills, as defiance to the governing SB Ordinance would warrant the issuance of Notice of Charge;
Direct the SIWASS Manager to coordinate with the electronic system service-provider to enable the automatic calculation of interest in the electronic system for ease of collection, monitoring and data gathering;
Encourage the SIWASS Manager to prepare a plan containing the measures to boost the revenue and lower the operational expenses of SIWASS, with the end-view of ensuring the financial viability of the enterprise;
Require the SIWASS Manager and the MEEDO Manager to prepare a separate financial report, subject for review by the Municipal Accountant to determine the financial condition and performance of the SIWASS.

We recommended that management:
Instruct the payees to identify the location of pipe repairs, and plate number of vehicles subject of reimbursement and direct the GSO to reconstruct and maintain a repair history on this regard;
Enjoin the municipal employees to avoid incurring reimbursements on repairs and maintenance and strictly comply with the requirements under Section 9.1.3.4 of COA Circular 2012-001 for the related payments thereon.

Require the Municipal Accountant to record first the purchases of drugs, medicines, medical and laboratory supplies as inventory;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and the Supply Officer to maintain and update the stock cards for each inventory item;
Direct the concerned RHU Personnel and Supply Officer to practice the use of RIS for every requisition and issuance of inventories;
Instruct the Supply Officer to prepare and submit monthly the Report of Supplies and Materials Issued (RSMI) to the Municipal Accountant as basis for the recording of expenses for inventories consumed or distributed; and
Require the Supply Officer and the Municipal Accountant to conduct physical inventory-taking at least on a semestral basis and reconcile the same with the balances in the stock cards.

Provide for a conclusion/ judgment for each beneficiary cases;
Confer with DSWD-Regional Office No. 10 on the results of the revalidation and obtain written conformance for each conclusion;
Seek a written advice from DSWD- Regional Office No. 10 as to the courses of action if recipients are affirmed to be ineligible/ duplicate;
Instruct the MSWDO to update the details in the SAC which may be useful for future reference.

